### fastp Trimming QC Summary Table

The file `fastp_logs_ryan_full_summary.tsv` summarizes read-quality metrics from the per-sample `fastp` JSON reports. Each row represents one sample. The table compares read quality before and after trimming, allowing us to confirm that trimming improved or maintained read quality while retaining most reads.

| Column | Description |
|---|---|
| `sample` | Sample name. This matches the sequencing sample ID used throughout the pipeline. |
| `before_total_reads` | Total number of reads in the raw input FASTQ files before trimming. This includes both paired-end reads. |
| `after_total_reads` | Total number of reads remaining after `fastp` trimming and filtering. |
| `reads_retained_percent` | Percentage of reads retained after trimming. Calculated as `(after_total_reads / before_total_reads) × 100`. |
| `before_q20_rate` | Fraction of bases with Phred quality score ≥ Q20 before trimming. Q20 corresponds to ~99% base-call accuracy. |
| `after_q20_rate` | Fraction of bases with Phred quality score ≥ Q20 after trimming. Higher values indicate that low-quality bases were removed or trimmed. |
| `before_q30_rate` | Fraction of bases with Phred quality score ≥ Q30 before trimming. Q30 corresponds to ~99.9% base-call accuracy. |
| `after_q30_rate` | Fraction of bases with Phred quality score ≥ Q30 after trimming. This is a stricter quality metric than Q20. |
| `before_gc_content` | Fraction of bases that are G or C before trimming. For example, `0.58` means 58% GC content. |
| `after_gc_content` | Fraction of bases that are G or C after trimming. This is used to check whether trimming strongly changed base composition. |

### Notes on Quality Scores

FASTQ files store sequencing quality as characters, not regular numbers. For example, a read may have a quality line like:

```text
IIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIII


Each character represents the confidence of one base call. These characters are converted into Phred quality scores. A Q20 base has an estimated error rate of 1 in 100 bases, or ~99% accuracy. A Q30 base has an estimated error rate of 1 in 1,000 bases, or ~99.9% accuracy.

Interpretation
The trimming QC showed that the raw reads were already high quality. Across all 1,116 samples, the mean Q30 rate increased from 95.39% before trimming to 97.49% after trimming. The mean read-retention rate was 95.84%, indicating that fastp removed low-quality/adaptor-contaminated sequence while retaining most reads. GC content remained nearly unchanged before and after trimming, suggesting that trimming did not strongly bias base composition.
